<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1C96B3F7BFE10FB34" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1C96B3F7BFE10FB34" blockId="30.[782,1367,691,1113]" lastBlockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1C96B3F7BFB8AFC08" box="[782,1036,883,916]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 
<quantity id="4CDE9B27CA4EFFA1CEA03F7BFAD6FC08" box="[1221,1360,883,916]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" metricValueMax="3.8" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" unit="cm" value="31.0" valueMax="38.0" valueMin="24.0">24-38 cm</quantity>
, tail 
<quantity id="4CDE9B27CA4EFFA1C92D3F97FC56FC20" box="[840,976,927,956]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" unit="cm" value="18.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="16.0">16-21 cm</quantity>
. The Amazon Weasel has a long, slender body and short limbs. The pelage is reddish to dark brown, with paler undersides. The underparts have a longitudinal median stripe of the same color as the upper parts. The tail is uniformly brown. The plantar surfaces on the feet are nearly naked.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC238BBFB67FB4C" box="[167,1249,1203,1232]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC238BBFB67FB4C" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" box="[167,1249,1203,1232]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC238BBFE93FB4C" box="[167,277,1203,1232]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Habitat.</emphasis>
Has been reported from primary forest and humid riparian habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC238DEFD1FFB6B" box="[167,665,1238,1271]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC238DEFD1FFB6B" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" box="[167,665,1238,1271]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC238DEFE2AFB6B" box="[167,428,1238,1271]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Nothing known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC03909FD42FADA" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="activity">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC03909FD42FADA" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC03909FE04FA82" box="[165,386,1281,1310]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Activity pattern.</emphasis>
Possibly diurnal: a group of four were seen around 10:00 h. Has been found denning in a hollow tree stump.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC23958FAB5FA09" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC23958FAB5FA09" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC23958FCE2FAF1" box="[167,868,1360,1389]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Said to be primarily terrestrial, but also reported to be a good swimmer and climber. Has been seen in a group offour.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC23997FD9DFA20" box="[167,539,1439,1468]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC23997FD9DFA20" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" box="[167,539,1439,1468]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC23997FEAAFA20" box="[167,300,1439,1468]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Breeding.</emphasis>
Nothing known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CAC239CEFF7AF9C5" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CAC239CEFF7AF9C5" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
<emphasis id="B952EAD0CA4EFFA1CAC239CEFD88FA7F" box="[167,526,1478,1507]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern in The 
<collectionCode id="ED37AE07CA4EFFA1CE7F39CEFBEFFA7F" box="[1050,1129,1478,1507]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">IUCN</collectionCode>
Red List. One of the least known species within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C264D41CA4EFFA1C8C039E1FCC5F996" authorityName="Fischer" authorityYear="1817" box="[677,835,1513,1546]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Mustelidae</taxonomicName>
. Amazon Weasels are a high priority for field studies to learn more about their natural history, ecology, and conservation status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33C6549CA4EFFA1CACD3A6FFB9BF91C" box="[168,1053,1639,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649" type="bibRefCitation_list">
<paragraph id="8B9936C2CA4EFFA1CACD3A6FFB9BF91C" blockId="30.[165,1370,1120,1664]" box="[168,1053,1639,1664]" pageId="30" pageNumber="649">
